**Sec. 40001. Coast Guard Mission Readiness.**

This section appropriates $24.593 billion for the Coast Guard for fiscal year 2025, to remain available until September 30, 2029. The funds are allocated for various purposes, including the procurement and acquisition of aircraft, cutters, and shore infrastructure, as well as for enhancing operational resilience and security of the maritime border. Specific allocations include $1.142 billion for fixed-wing aircraft, $2.283 billion for rotary-wing aircraft, and $4.3 billion each for Offshore Patrol Cutters and Polar Security Cutters.

**Sec. 40002. Spectrum Auctions.**

This section amends the Communications Act of 1934 to extend the general auction authority of the Federal Communications Commission (FCC) until September 30, 2034, with exceptions for specific frequency bands. It requires the FCC to complete a system of competitive bidding for at least 100 megahertz in the 3.98-4.2 gigahertz band within two years of enactment. Additionally, the Assistant Secretary of Commerce for Communications and Information, in consultation with the FCC, must identify 500 megahertz of frequencies for reallocation to non-Federal use, with a schedule for identification and auctioning of these frequencies.

**Sec. 40003. Air Traffic Control Improvements.**

This section appropriates $12.5 billion for the Federal Aviation Administration (FAA) for fiscal year 2025 to improve or maintain aviation safety. The funds are allocated for telecommunications infrastructure modernization, radar systems replacement, runway safety technologies, and the construction of a new air route traffic control center. It also includes provisions for the divestment and integration of existing facilities, as well as the deployment of remote tower technology at untowered airports.

**Sec. 40004. Space Launch and Reentry Licensing and Permitting User Fees.**

This section establishes a new user fee system for space launches and reentries, with fees increasing annually based on the weight of the payload and a fixed amount. The fees are to be deposited into a new account in the Treasury, known as the "Office of Commercial Space Transportation Launch and Reentry Licensing and Permitting Fund," and are to be used for expenses of the Office of Commercial Space Transportation and to carry out specific provisions of the FAA Reauthorization Act of 2024.

**Sec. 40005. Mars Missions, Artemis Missions, and Moon to Mars Program.**

This section appropriates $9.995 billion for fiscal year 2025 to support Mars missions, Artemis missions, and the Moon to Mars program. The funds are allocated for various purposes, including the procurement of a Mars telecommunications orbiter, the Gateway program, the Space Launch System for Artemis IV and V, the Orion spacecraft, the operation of the International Space Station, and infrastructure improvements at manned spaceflight centers.

**Sec. 40006. Corporate Average Fuel Economy Civil Penalties.**

This section eliminates civil penalties for manufacturers failing to meet Corporate Average Fuel Economy (CAFE) standards, reducing the penalties from $5 and $10 per 0.1 mpg shortfall to $0.00. The amendments take effect on the date of enactment and apply to all model years for which the Secretary of Transportation has not provided a notification specifying the penalty due.

**Sec. 40007. Payments for Lease of Metropolitan Washington Airports.**

This section amends the lease payments for the Metropolitan Washington Airports Authority, increasing the annual payment from $3 million in 1987 dollars to $15 million in 2027 dollars starting in 2027. The Secretary and the Airports Authority are required to renegotiate the level of lease payments at least once every 10 years to ensure that the amount specified is not less than $15 million in 2027 dollars.

**Sec. 40008. Rescission of Certain Amounts for the National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration.**

This section rescinds any unobligated balances of amounts appropriated or otherwise made available by sections 40001, 40002, 40003, and 40004 of Public Law 117-169 for the National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration (NOAA).

**Sec. 40009. Reduction in Annual Transfers to Travel Promotion Fund.**

This section reduces the annual transfer to the Travel Promotion Fund from $100 million to $20 million.

**Sec. 40010. Treatment of Unobligated Funds for Alternative Fuel and Low-Emission Aviation Technology.**

This section rescinds any unobligated balances of amounts made available by section 40007(a) of title IV of Public Law 117-169 for alternative fuel and low-emission aviation technology.

**Sec. 40011. Rescission of Amounts Appropriated to Public Wireless Supply Chain Innovation Fund.**

This section rescinds $850 million of unobligated balances of amounts made available under section 106(a) of the CHIPS Act of 2022 for the Public Wireless Supply Chain Innovation Fund. [end of text]


